"**Comparison of Policies: Ranil Wickremesinghe vs. Dilith Jayaweera**\n\n| **Policy Area** | **Ranil Wickremesinghe** | **Dilith Jayaweera** |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| 1. Economic Policy and Growth Strategies | Establish Theravada Trade Economy, add two sectors to compete with private sector, create 100,000 new employment opportunities | Prioritize investments for entrepreneurial development, encourage strategic investments in infrastructure and service development |\n| 2. Education Reform and Innovation | Modernize school infrastructure and teacher training by 2027, introduce program to equip teachers with new knowledge and training in 2025 | Establish Sri Lanka Education Index, strengthen free education and leverage private education within a structured framework |\n| 3. Energy and Sustainability | Obtain 70% of power supply network from renewable energy sources by 2030, encourage investments in renewable energy production | Implement national energy efficiency policy, invest in resilient system technologies to improve energy efficiency and reliability |\n| 4. Healthcare System and Public Health | Establish private hospitals in all nine provinces, introduce resilient healthcare insurance scheme | Introduce national health insurance fund to provide financial coverage for all citizens, establish authority to regulate indigenous medical practices |\n| 5. National Security and Defense | Introduce Security (Special Provisions) Act, implement One Rank - One Pension system for Tri Forces | Implement defense strategy to preempt and minimize threats, employ advanced surveillance technology to safeguard territorial integrity |\n| 6. Legal Framework and Judicial Reform | Introduce new Constitution within a year after Parliamentary Election, establish new election procedure based on mixed electoral system | Expand legal aid services to ensure access to justice for all citizens, implement reforms to criminal justice system |\n| 7. Transportation and Mobility | Provide sustainable green transport services, establish charging centers for electric vehicles | Create integrated transport plan by combining railways, buses, boats, and taxi services, develop scientific mechanism to efficiently utilize railway infrastructure |\n| 8. Infrastructure Development and Modernization | Upgrade tourism infrastructure to accommodate increased visitors, modernize school infrastructure to face era of technology | Develop comprehensive national plan to improve energy efficiency across residential, commercial, and industrial sectors, initiate projects to rehabilitate and develop rural roads |\n| 9. Foreign Policy and International Relations | Strengthen institutions and recover stolen assets through international cooperation, collaborate with international partners to ensure opportunities are accessible to all | Adopt flexible, multi-aligned foreign policy based on national interest, provide continuous training and support to ensure ambassadors are well-equipped to handle modern diplomatic challenges |\n\n**Common Policies:**\n\n* Emphasis on renewable energy and sustainability\n* Importance of education reform and innovation\n* Need for healthcare system and public health improvements\n* Focus on national security and defense\n\n**Unique/Innovative Policies:**\n\n* Ranil Wickremesinghe: Establishing Theravada Trade Economy, creating 100,000 new employment opportunities\n* Dilith Jayaweera: Establishing Sri Lanka Education Index, introducing national health insurance fund to provide financial coverage for all citizens\n\n**Analysis:**\n\n* Ranil Wickremesinghe's policies focus on economic growth, education reform, and national security, with an emphasis on establishing a strong economy and promoting Sri Lanka's global presence.\n* Dilith Jayaweera's policies prioritize entrepreneurial development, education reform, and healthcare system improvements, with a focus on creating a globally competitive and dynamic production economy.\n* Both candidates emphasize the importance of renewable energy and sustainability, as well as the need for healthcare system and public health improvements.\n* Ranil Wickremesinghe's policies seem to focus more on short-term goals, such as creating 100,000 new employment opportunities, while Dilith Jayaweera's policies appear to focus on long-term goals, such as establishing a comprehensive national plan to improve energy efficiency across residential, commercial, and industrial sectors."